still being effective and
remaining effective?

00:01:31.910 --> 00:01:32.840
&gt;&gt; Yeah.
Sure.

00:01:32.840 --> 00:01:33.900
Um, so the question is

00:01:33.900 --> 00:01:35.830
how you deal with burnout as
a founder.

00:01:35.830 --> 00:01:39.650
Uh, this, the answer to this
is just that it sucks and

00:01:39.650 --> 00:01:40.700
you keep going.

00:01:40.700 --> 00:01:43.340
Um, unlike a student, where
you can sort of throw up

00:01:43.340 --> 00:01:45.870
your hands and say, you know
what, I&#39;m really burned out.

00:01:45.870 --> 00:01:48.460
I&#39;m just gonna like get bad
grades this quarter.

00:01:48.460 --> 00:01:50.750
Uh, one of the hard parts
about running a start up

00:01:50.750 --> 00:01:52.060
is that it&#39;s real life.

00:01:52.060 --> 00:01:55.420
And um, you just have to get
through it.

00:01:55.420 --> 00:01:57.080
Uh, the canonical advice is
like go

00:01:57.080 --> 00:01:58.390
on vacation or whatever.

00:01:58.390 --> 00:02:00.140
Um, that never works for
founders.

00:02:00.140 --> 00:02:02.285
It&#39;s sort of all consuming
in this way.

00:02:02.285 --> 00:02:04.380
It&#39;s very difficult to
understand.

00:02:04.380 --> 00:02:07.190
So what you do is you just
keep going.

00:02:07.190 --> 00:02:10.160
Um, you rely on people uh,
it&#39;s like really important.

00:02:10.160 --> 00:02:11.720
And founder depression is
this serious thing.

00:02:11.720 --> 00:02:14.180
And you need to have a
support network.

00:02:14.180 --> 00:02:16.670
Um, but the way through
burnout is just to address

00:02:16.670 --> 00:02:19.140
the challenges, address the
things that are going wrong,

00:02:19.140 --> 00:02:20.702
and you&#39;ll eventually feel
better.

00:02:20.702 --> 00:02:24.800
All right, so, last week we,
or last lecture we

