covered the idea and the
product, um, and I want to

00:02:28.850 --> 00:02:31.030
just emphasize that if you
don&#39;t get those right,

00:02:31.030 --> 00:02:33.360
none of the rest of this
going to save you.

00:02:33.360 --> 00:02:36.550
Um, today, we&#39;re gonna talk
about how to hire ah, and

00:02:36.550 --> 00:02:37.130
how to execute.

00:02:38.210 --> 00:02:40.000
Hopefully you don&#39;t execute
the people you hire.

00:02:40.000 --> 00:02:40.500
Um.

00:02:41.730 --> 00:02:43.212
Sometimes.

00:02:43.212 --> 00:02:47.130
Uh, so, first, I wanna talk
about co-founder.

00:02:47.130 --> 00:02:49.970
Um, co-founder relationships
are among the most

00:02:49.970 --> 00:02:51.840
important in the entire
company.

00:02:51.840 --> 00:02:54.450
Um, and everyone says that
you need to watch out for

00:02:54.450 --> 00:02:57.200
tension brewing among
co-founders, and

00:02:57.200 --> 00:02:59.180
address them immediately,
and that&#39;s all true.

00:02:59.180 --> 00:03:01.330
And certainly in YC&#39;s case.

00:03:01.330 --> 00:03:03.630
The number one cause of
early death for

00:03:03.630 --> 00:03:05.549
start ups is, is co-founder
blow ups.

00:03:06.720 --> 00:03:09.125
But for some reason a lot of
treat choosing their

00:03:09.125 --> 00:03:10.710
co-founder with even less
importance than

00:03:10.710 --> 00:03:12.500
they put on hiring.

00:03:12.500 --> 00:03:14.060
Um, don&#39;t do this.

00:03:14.060 --> 00:03:15.660
This is one of the most
important decisions you

00:03:15.660 --> 00:03:17.400
make in the life of your
start up,

00:03:17.400 --> 00:03:18.450
and you get treated as such.

00:03:18.450 --> 00:03:19.750
And for some reason,

00:03:19.750 --> 00:03:22.460
students are really bad at
this.

00:03:22.460 --> 00:03:23.150
They just pick someone,

00:03:23.150 --> 00:03:24.250
they&#39;re like I wanna start a
business,

00:03:24.250 --> 00:03:25.420
you wanna start a business,
let&#39;s start it,

00:03:25.420 --> 00:03:26.450
start it together.

00:03:26.450 --> 00:03:29.760
Um, there are these, like,
co-founder dating things

00:03:29.760 --> 00:03:31.900
where you&#39;re like hey, I&#39;m
looking for a co-founder.

00:03:31.900 --> 00:03:32.740
We don&#39;t really know each
other,

00:03:32.740 --> 00:03:33.400
let&#39;s start a company.

00:03:33.400 --> 00:03:35.550
And this is like crazy.

00:03:35.550 --> 00:03:38.700
Um, you would never hire
someone like this, and yet

00:03:38.700 --> 00:03:39.330
people are willing to

00:03:39.330 --> 00:03:40.780
choose their business
partners this way.

00:03:41.840 --> 00:03:44.230
Um, it&#39;s really, really bad.

00:03:44.230 --> 00:03:45.860
And choosing a random
co-founder or

00:03:45.860 --> 00:03:48.070
choosing someone you don&#39;t
have a long history with.

00:03:48.070 --> 00:03:49.580
Choosing someone that you&#39;re
not friends with.

00:03:49.580 --> 00:03:52.130
So that when things are
really going wrong, you have

00:03:52.130 --> 00:03:54.560
this sort of past history to
bind you together.

00:03:54.560 --> 00:03:57.100
Um, usually ends up in
disaster.

00:03:57.100 --> 00:04:01.404
We had one YC batch where
nine of about 75 companies

00:04:01.404 --> 00:04:04.090
added on a random co-founder
between when we

00:04:04.090 --> 00:04:05.510
interviewed the companies
and when they started,

00:04:05.510 --> 00:04:09.070
and all nine of those teams
fell apart in the next year.

00:04:09.070 --> 00:04:10.579
Uh, the track record for
founders that

00:04:10.579 --> 00:04:12.370
don&#39;t already know each
other is really bad.

00:04:13.610 --> 00:04:16.840
Um, a good way to meet a
co-founder is in college.

00:04:16.840 --> 00:04:17.760
If you&#39;re not in college and

00:04:17.760 --> 00:04:19.920
you don&#39;t know a co-founder,
the next best thing I

00:04:19.920 --> 00:04:21.485
think is to go work in an
interesting company.

00:04:21.485 --> 00:04:22.985
If you work at Facebook or
Google or

00:04:22.985 --> 00:04:24.175
something like that, um,

00:04:24.175 --> 00:04:26.680
it&#39;s probably almost as
co-founder Rich at Stanford.

00:04:28.280 --> 00:04:30.490
It&#39;s better to have no
co-founder uh,

00:04:30.490 --> 00:04:32.120
than have a bad co-founder,
but

00:04:32.120 --> 00:04:33.920
it&#39;s still bad to be a solo
founder.

00:04:33.920 --> 00:04:35.400
Um, I was just looking at

00:04:35.400 --> 00:04:36.586
the stats here before we
started.

00:04:36.586 --> 00:04:37.920
For the top, and

00:04:37.920 --> 00:04:39.690
I may have missed one cause
I was counting quickly, but

00:04:39.690 --> 00:04:42.700
I think, but for the top 20
most valuable YC

00:04:42.700 --> 00:04:46.500
companies um, all of them
have at least two founders.

00:04:46.500 --> 00:04:49.437
Uh, and we, we probably fund
at a rate of something like

00:04:49.437 --> 00:04:51.640
one out of ten solo teams.

00:04:51.640 --> 00:04:52.813
Uh, so best of all,

00:04:52.813 --> 00:04:55.880
founder you know, co-founder
you know.

00:04:55.880 --> 00:04:58.440
Um, better than that or not
as good as that but

00:04:58.440 --> 00:05:00.220
still okay, solo founder.

00:05:00.220 --> 00:05:01.580
Random founder you meet.

00:05:01.580 --> 00:05:03.820
Uh, again students do this
for some reason.

00:05:03.820 --> 00:05:04.460
Really, really bad.

00:05:05.720 --> 00:05:08.080
Uh, so as you&#39;re thinking
about co-founders and

00:05:08.080 --> 00:05:09.800
people that could be good,

00:05:09.800 --> 00:05:11.930
there&#39;s a question of what
you&#39;re looking for, right?

00:05:11.930 --> 00:05:14.350
And at YC we have this
public phrase.

00:05:14.350 --> 00:05:16.220
Um, and it&#39;s relentlessly
resourceful.

00:05:16.220 --> 00:05:18.030
And everyone&#39;s heard about
it.

00:05:18.030 --> 00:05:19.950
And I think that really is a
very good description for

00:05:19.950 --> 00:05:21.840
what you&#39;re looking for with
co-founders.

00:05:21.840 --> 00:05:23.270
Um, you definitely need

00:05:23.270 --> 00:05:25.646
relentlessly resourceful
co-founders.

00:05:25.646 --> 00:05:27.970
Um, but there&#39;s a more
colorful example that we

00:05:27.970 --> 00:05:30.090
share at the YC kickoff.

00:05:30.090 --> 00:05:32.220
Um, Paul Gram started using
this, and

00:05:32.220 --> 00:05:33.110
I&#39;ve kept it going.

00:05:33.110 --> 00:05:35.057
Um, so you&#39;re looking for

00:05:35.057 --> 00:05:39.070
co-founders that need to be
unflappable, tough.

00:05:39.070 --> 00:05:41.030
They know what to do in
every situation.

00:05:41.030 --> 00:05:41.690
They act quickly.

00:05:41.690 --> 00:05:42.470
They&#39;re decisive.

00:05:42.470 --> 00:05:43.220
They&#39;re creative.

00:05:43.220 --> 00:05:44.820
They&#39;re ready for anything.

00:05:44.820 --> 00:05:46.890
Um, and it turns out that
there&#39;s a model for

00:05:46.890 --> 00:05:48.960
this in, in pop culture.

00:05:48.960 --> 00:05:50.950
And it sounds really dumb,
but

00:05:50.950 --> 00:05:52.240
it&#39;s at least very
memorable.

00:05:52.240 --> 00:05:54.110
And we&#39;ve told every class
of YC this for

00:05:54.110 --> 00:05:57.110
a long time, and I think it
helps them.

00:05:57.110 --> 00:06:00.300
Um, and that model is James
Bond.

00:06:00.300 --> 00:06:02.790
Um, and again it sounds
crazy but it, it, uh,

00:06:02.790 --> 00:06:05.790
it will at least stick in
your memory and, and

00:06:05.790 --> 00:06:08.620
you need someone that
behaves like James Bond

00:06:08.620 --> 00:06:10.480
more than you need someone
that is you

00:06:10.480 --> 00:06:11.870
know an expert in some
particular domain.

00:06:14.310 --> 00:06:15.160
As I mentioned earlier,

00:06:15.160 --> 00:06:16.930
you really want to know your
co-founders for

00:06:16.930 --> 00:06:19.140
a while, ideally years.

00:06:19.140 --> 00:06:21.100
This is true for early hires
as well.

00:06:21.100 --> 00:06:23.200
But incidentally, more
people get this right for

00:06:23.200 --> 00:06:26.689
early hires, than they do
for co-founders.

00:06:26.689 --> 00:06:28.470
Uh, so again, take advantage
of school.

00:06:29.700 --> 00:06:32.060
Um, in addition to
relentlessly resourceful,

00:06:32.060 --> 00:06:34.820
you want a tough and a calm
co-founder.

00:06:34.820 --> 00:06:37.060
Uh, there are all the
obvious things like smart.

00:06:37.060 --> 00:06:39.590
But everyone knows that you
want a smart co-founder.

00:06:39.590 --> 00:06:41.330
Uh, most people don&#39;t
prioritize tough and

00:06:41.330 --> 00:06:43.020
calm well enough.

00:06:43.020 --> 00:06:45.300
Especially if you feel like
you yourself aren&#39;t,

00:06:45.300 --> 00:06:47.300
you need a co-founder who
is.

00:06:47.300 --> 00:06:48.510
Um, if you&#39;re not technical,
and

00:06:48.510 --> 00:06:50.570
hopefully most people in
this room are,

00:06:50.570 --> 00:06:52.940
you really want a technical
co-founder.

00:06:52.940 --> 00:06:54.012
There&#39;s this weird thing
going on in

00:06:54.012 --> 00:06:56.215
start ups right now where
it&#39;s become popular to say,

00:06:56.215 --> 00:06:57.330
like you know what?

00:06:57.330 --> 00:06:58.590
We don&#39;t need technical
founders,

00:06:58.590 --> 00:06:59.330
we&#39;re gonna hire people,

00:06:59.330 --> 00:07:01.420
We&#39;re just gonna be great
managers.

00:07:01.420 --> 00:07:04.250
Um, that doesn&#39;t work too
well, in our experience.

00:07:04.250 --> 00:07:04.770
In a software,

00:07:04.770 --> 00:07:07.250
people really should be
starting software companies.

00:07:07.250 --> 00:07:08.970
Media people should be
starting media companies.

00:07:10.590 --> 00:07:13.760
Um, so and in the YC
experience, two or

00:07:13.760 --> 00:07:16.130
three co-founders seems to
be about perfect.

00:07:16.130 --> 00:07:18.270
Um, one obviously not great,

00:07:18.270 --> 00:07:21.240
five really bad, four works
sometimes, but uh, two or

00:07:21.240 --> 00:07:23.630
three I think is what to
target.

00:07:24.890 --> 00:07:27.560
Okay, the second part of how
to hire.

00:07:27.560 --> 00:07:29.220
Um, try not to.

00:07:29.220 --> 00:07:30.820
So one of the weird things
that you&#39;ll notice if

00:07:30.820 --> 00:07:32.840
you start a company is that
everyone asks you

00:07:32.840 --> 00:07:33.930
how many employees you have.

00:07:33.930 --> 00:07:36.240
And this is the metric
people use to sort of

00:07:36.240 --> 00:07:39.180
judge how real your start up
is and how cool you are.

00:07:39.180 --> 00:07:40.970
Um, and if you say you have
a high number of employees,

00:07:40.970 --> 00:07:42.260
they&#39;re really impressed.

00:07:42.260 --> 00:07:44.290
And if you say you have a
low number of employees

00:07:44.290 --> 00:07:47.790
then, then you sound like
sort of this little joke.

00:07:47.790 --> 00:07:50.870
Um, but actually it sucks to
have a lot of employees and

00:07:50.870 --> 00:07:53.400
you should be proud of how
few employees you can have.

00:07:53.400 --> 00:07:55.700
Lots of employees ends up
with things like a high burn

00:07:55.700 --> 00:07:57.760
rate, meaning that you&#39;re
losing a lot of money every

00:07:57.760 --> 00:08:01.320
month, complexity, tension,
slow decision making.

00:08:01.320 --> 00:08:03.180
The list goes on but it&#39;s
nothing good.

00:08:03.180 --> 00:08:05.960
So you want to, you want to
be proud of how much you can

00:08:05.960 --> 00:08:08.350
get done with a small number
of employees.

00:08:08.350 --> 00:08:11.160
Um, many of the best YC
companies have had

00:08:11.160 --> 00:08:12.840
phenomenally small number of
employees for

00:08:12.840 --> 00:08:15.480
the first year, sometimes
none besides the founders.

00:08:15.480 --> 00:08:16.640
Um, they really try to

00:08:16.640 --> 00:08:18.480
stay small as long as they
possibly can.

00:08:19.910 --> 00:08:21.610
At the beginning, you should
only hire when you

00:08:21.610 --> 00:08:22.900
have the desperate need to.

00:08:22.900 --> 00:08:24.756
Later you need to learn how
to hire fast to scale up

00:08:24.756 --> 00:08:25.920
the company.

00:08:25.920 --> 00:08:27.142
But in the early days uh,

00:08:27.142 --> 00:08:30.460
the goal should be not to
hire, not too higher.

00:08:30.460 --> 00:08:33.360
And one of the reasons this
is so bad is that

00:08:33.360 --> 00:08:36.860
the cost of getting a early
hire wrong is really high.

00:08:36.860 --> 00:08:40.300
Um, in fact a lot of the
companies that I have been

00:08:40.300 --> 00:08:43.360
very involved with that have
had a very bad first hire

00:08:43.360 --> 00:08:44.260
in the first three or

00:08:44.260 --> 00:08:45.680
so employees never recover
from it.

00:08:45.680 --> 00:08:47.390
It just kills the company.

00:08:47.390 --> 00:08:50.720
Um, Airbnb spent five months
interviewing their first

00:08:50.720 --> 00:08:52.700
employee before they hired
someone.

00:08:52.700 --> 00:08:55.450
And in their first year they
only hired two people.

00:08:55.450 --> 00:08:57.740
Um, before they hired a
single person they,

00:08:57.740 --> 00:08:59.650
they wrote down a list of
the cultural values that

00:08:59.650 --> 00:09:01.820
they wanted any Airbnb
employee to have.

00:09:03.410 --> 00:09:06.010
One of those was that you
had to bleed Airbnb.

00:09:06.010 --> 00:09:07.000
And if you didn&#39;t sort of
agree to

00:09:07.000 --> 00:09:08.610
that they just wouldn&#39;t hire
you.

00:09:08.610 --> 00:09:11.510
Um, as an example of how
intense Brian Chesky is,

00:09:11.510 --> 00:09:13.100
he&#39;s there being CEO.

00:09:13.100 --> 00:09:15.558
Um, he use to ask people
before he hired them at

00:09:15.558 --> 00:09:18.130
Airbnb, if they would take
the job if they got a

00:09:18.130 --> 00:09:21.050
medical diagnosis that they
got one year left to live.

00:09:21.050 --> 00:09:22.350
Um, he wanted them to be
that committed.

00:09:22.350 --> 00:09:24.980
Later he decided that, that
was like a little too crazy.

00:09:24.980 --> 00:09:28.450
&gt;&gt; Um, and I think he
relaxed it to ten years.

00:09:28.450 --> 00:09:30.689
But last I heard, he still
asks that question.

00:09:33.370 --> 00:09:36.110
Um, but like, you know,
these hires really matter.

00:09:36.110 --> 00:09:38.600
These people are what go on
to define your company.

