Ideas by themselves are not
worth anything.

00:30:18.290 --> 00:30:20.520
Only executing well is what,
what adds value,

00:30:20.520 --> 00:30:21.480
or what creates value.

00:30:23.130 --> 00:30:25.860
A big part of execution is
just putting in the effort.

00:30:25.860 --> 00:30:27.880
Um, but there is a lot you
can learn about how to

00:30:27.880 --> 00:30:29.370
be good at it and so we&#39;re
gonna have I

00:30:29.370 --> 00:30:31.730
think three classes that
just talk about this.

00:30:33.320 --> 00:30:36.284
Uh, so the CEO, people have
asked me a bunch of

00:30:36.284 --> 00:30:38.795
times like the jobs of the
start up CEO.

00:30:38.795 --> 00:30:41.393
And there are probably more
than five but, you know,

00:30:41.393 --> 00:30:44.540
here are five that come up a
lot in the early days.

00:30:44.540 --> 00:30:46.420
Um, the first four,

00:30:46.420 --> 00:30:48.830
I think everyone thinks of
as CEO jobs.

00:30:48.830 --> 00:30:49.506
Set the vision.

00:30:49.506 --> 00:30:50.489
Raise money.

00:30:50.489 --> 00:30:52.919
Evangelize the company to
people you&#39;re trying to

00:30:52.919 --> 00:30:53.432
recruit.

00:30:53.432 --> 00:30:55.308
Existing employees,
partners, press,

00:30:55.308 --> 00:30:56.970
customers, everybody.

00:30:56.970 --> 00:30:58.380
Hire and manage the team.

00:30:58.380 --> 00:31:03.030
Um, but the fifth one is
setting the execution bar,

00:31:03.030 --> 00:31:03.940
and this is not something
that

00:31:03.940 --> 00:31:06.470
most founders get excited
about.

00:31:06.470 --> 00:31:08.630
Probably think about
themselves doing that I

00:31:08.630 --> 00:31:10.900
think is actually one of the
critical CEO roles.

00:31:10.900 --> 00:31:13.270
And no one but the CEO can
do this.

00:31:13.270 --> 00:31:17.570
Um execution gets divided
into two, two key questions.

00:31:17.570 --> 00:31:19.580
One can you figure out what
to do?

00:31:19.580 --> 00:31:20.860
And two can you get it done?

00:31:22.300 --> 00:31:25.970
Um so I wanna talk about two
parts of getting it done.

00:31:25.970 --> 00:31:28.010
Assuming that you&#39;ve already
figured out what to do.

00:31:28.010 --> 00:31:30.120
Um, and those are focus and
intensity.

00:31:31.300 --> 00:31:35.120
Ah, so, so focus is
critical.

00:31:35.120 --> 00:31:38.240
Um, one of my favorite
questions to ask founders

00:31:38.240 --> 00:31:40.580
is what they&#39;re spending
their time and money on.

00:31:40.580 --> 00:31:42.700
Um, this reveals almost
everything,

00:31:42.700 --> 00:31:45.040
about what founders think is
important.

00:31:45.040 --> 00:31:46.560
One of the hardest parts
about being a founder.

00:31:47.620 --> 00:31:48.670
Is it there are 100
important

00:31:48.670 --> 00:31:50.160
things competing for your
attention every day.

00:31:50.160 --> 00:31:53.560
Um, and you have to identify
the right two or three, work

00:31:53.560 --> 00:31:57.000
on those and then ignore or
delegate or defer the rest.

00:31:57.000 --> 00:31:58.180
And a lot of these things
that,

00:31:58.180 --> 00:32:00.450
that founders think are
really important, you know.

00:32:00.450 --> 00:32:01.880
Interviewing a lot of
different law firms,

00:32:01.880 --> 00:32:04.290
going to conferences,
recruiting advisors,

00:32:04.290 --> 00:32:06.970
whatever, they just don&#39;t
matter, right?

00:32:06.970 --> 00:32:10.360
And what really does matter,
varies with time but

00:32:10.360 --> 00:32:12.841
it&#39;s an important piece of
May Day advice.

00:32:12.841 --> 00:32:14.170
You need to figure out what
the two or

00:32:14.170 --> 00:32:17.500
three most important things
are and then just do those.

00:32:17.500 --> 00:32:19.352
And you can only have two or
three things every day,

00:32:19.352 --> 00:32:21.088
because everything else will
just come at you.

00:32:21.088 --> 00:32:22.389
You know fires of the day,
and

00:32:22.389 --> 00:32:24.837
if you don&#39;t get really good
at setting what these two or

00:32:24.837 --> 00:32:26.790
three priorities are every
day.

00:32:26.790 --> 00:32:28.720
Um, you&#39;ll never be great at
actually getting stuff done.

00:32:31.210 --> 00:32:33.660
This is really hard for
founders right.

00:32:33.660 --> 00:32:34.780
Founders are people that get

00:32:34.780 --> 00:32:37.110
excited by starting new
things.

00:32:37.110 --> 00:32:39.400
Unfortunately, the trick to
great execution is to

00:32:39.400 --> 00:32:40.530
say no a lot.

00:32:40.530 --> 00:32:43.110
You know, you&#39;re saying no
97 times out of 100,

00:32:43.110 --> 00:32:45.370
um, and most founders find
that they have to

00:32:45.370 --> 00:32:48.090
make a very conscious effort
to do this.

00:32:48.090 --> 00:32:49.940
Most startups are not nearly
focused enough.

00:32:51.250 --> 00:32:52.840
They work really hard,
maybe, but

00:32:52.840 --> 00:32:54.560
they don&#39;t work hard on the
right things.

00:32:54.560 --> 00:32:56.020
And you&#39;ll still fail.

00:32:56.020 --> 00:32:57.120
Um, one of the great and

00:32:57.120 --> 00:33:00.570
terrible things about
starting a startup is that

00:33:00.570 --> 00:33:02.240
you get no credit for
trying.

00:33:02.240 --> 00:33:03.210
You only get points when you

00:33:03.210 --> 00:33:05.460
make something that the
market wants.

00:33:05.460 --> 00:33:07.770
So if you work really hard
on the wrong things.

00:33:07.770 --> 00:33:08.510
Uh, no one will care.

00:33:08.510 --> 00:33:11.610
So then there&#39;s this
question of how do

00:33:11.610 --> 00:33:14.310
you figure out what to focus
on each day?

00:33:14.310 --> 00:33:16.200
And this is where it&#39;s
really important to

00:33:16.200 --> 00:33:16.820
have goals.

00:33:18.000 --> 00:33:19.730
Most good founders that I
know uh,

00:33:19.730 --> 00:33:21.930
at any given time have a
small number of

00:33:21.930 --> 00:33:23.830
overarching goals for the
company.

00:33:23.830 --> 00:33:25.060
Everybody in the company
knows.

00:33:25.060 --> 00:33:26.920
Could be things like ship a
product by this date.

00:33:26.920 --> 00:33:29.130
You know, maintain this
growth rate,

00:33:29.130 --> 00:33:30.880
get this certain engagement
rate, hire for

00:33:30.880 --> 00:33:32.690
these key roles, get this
deal done.

00:33:32.690 --> 00:33:35.440
But anybody could tell you
in the company every week

00:33:35.440 --> 00:33:37.560
what are our, what are our
key goals?

00:33:37.560 --> 00:33:39.210
And then everybody executes
based off of that.

00:33:40.810 --> 00:33:42.590
The founder really does set
the focus.

00:33:42.590 --> 00:33:44.440
Um, whatever the founder
cares about,

00:33:44.440 --> 00:33:46.800
whatever the founders think
are the key goals.

00:33:46.800 --> 00:33:47.660
Um, that&#39;s going to

00:33:47.660 --> 00:33:49.930
be what the whole company
focuses on.

00:33:49.930 --> 00:33:52.560
And, and the best founders
repeat these goals over and

00:33:52.560 --> 00:33:53.850
over far more often than
they

00:33:53.850 --> 00:33:55.480
think they should need to.

00:33:55.480 --> 00:33:56.450
They put em up on the walls,

00:33:56.450 --> 00:33:57.880
they talk about them in one
on one&#39;s,

00:33:57.880 --> 00:33:59.410
all hands meeting every
week.

00:33:59.410 --> 00:34:03.820
Um, but it keeps the company
focused.

00:34:03.820 --> 00:34:06.615
One of the keys to focus on
why I said I think.

00:34:06.615 --> 00:34:09.610
Co-founders in different
places struggle is that

00:34:09.610 --> 00:34:12.520
you can&#39;t be focused without
really great communication.

00:34:12.520 --> 00:34:14.430
Um, even if you only have
say four or

00:34:14.430 --> 00:34:15.850
five people in a company.

00:34:15.850 --> 00:34:18.410
A small communication
breakdown is enough for

00:34:18.410 --> 00:34:20.350
everybody to be working on
slightly different things.

00:34:21.480 --> 00:34:23.030
Um, and then you lose focus
and

00:34:23.030 --> 00:34:24.590
the company just scrambles.

00:34:27.660 --> 00:34:32.260
I&#39;m going to talk about this
a little bit more later.

00:34:32.260 --> 00:34:33.900
Um, but growth and

00:34:33.900 --> 00:34:36.900
momentum are something you
can never lose focus on.

00:34:36.900 --> 00:34:41.340
Uh, growth and momentum are
what a start up lives on.

00:34:41.340 --> 00:34:44.160
Uh, and you always have to
focus on maintaining these.

00:34:44.160 --> 00:34:44.950
You should always know how
you

00:34:44.950 --> 00:34:46.530
are doing against your
metrics.

00:34:46.530 --> 00:34:47.710
You should have a weekly
review meeting every

00:34:47.710 --> 00:34:48.990
week and you should be

00:34:48.990 --> 00:34:52.120
extremely suspicious if
you&#39;re ever talking about.

00:34:52.120 --> 00:34:54.170
We&#39;re not focused on growth
right now,

00:34:54.170 --> 00:34:55.320
we&#39;re not growing that well
right now, but

00:34:55.320 --> 00:34:57.220
we&#39;re doing this other
thing, you know.

00:34:57.220 --> 00:34:59.010
We don&#39;t have, we don&#39;t have
a timeline for when we&#39;re

00:34:59.010 --> 00:35:01.610
gonna ship this cuz were
focused on this other thing.

00:35:01.610 --> 00:35:02.370
We&#39;re doing a rebrand,

00:35:02.370 --> 00:35:06.150
whatever, almost always a
disaster.

00:35:06.150 --> 00:35:08.120
So you wanna have the right
metrics and

00:35:08.120 --> 00:35:10.210
you want to be focused on
growing those metrics and

00:35:10.210 --> 00:35:11.300
having momentum.

00:35:11.300 --> 00:35:16.610
Um, don&#39;t, don&#39;t let the
company get distracted or

00:35:16.610 --> 00:35:18.250
excited by other things.

00:35:18.250 --> 00:35:21.620
Um, a common mistake is that
company&#39;s gets excited by

00:35:21.620 --> 00:35:22.130
their own PR.

00:35:23.280 --> 00:35:25.970
It&#39;s really easy to get PR
with no results and

00:35:25.970 --> 00:35:28.430
it feels like your actually
really cool.

00:35:28.430 --> 00:35:30.350
But in a year, you&#39;ll still
have nothing, and

00:35:30.350 --> 00:35:31.880
at that point you won&#39;t be
cool anymore.

00:35:31.880 --> 00:35:32.750
And you&#39;ll just be

00:35:32.750 --> 00:35:34.810
talking about these articles
from a year ago.

00:35:34.810 --> 00:35:36.520
That oh, you know, like
these Standford students

00:35:36.520 --> 00:35:38.320
start this new startup, it&#39;s
gonna be the next big thing.

00:35:38.320 --> 00:35:40.840
And now you have nothing,
and that sucks.

00:35:40.840 --> 00:35:42.970
Um, and then,

00:35:42.970 --> 00:35:45.730
as I mentioned already, be
in the same space.

00:35:45.730 --> 00:35:48.110
Ah, this is like,

00:35:48.110 --> 00:35:49.640
I think this is pretty much
a non starter.

00:35:49.640 --> 00:35:52.700
Remote co-founding teams is
just really really hard.

00:35:52.700 --> 00:35:54.510
It slows down the cycle time
more

00:35:54.510 --> 00:35:55.950
than anybody ever thinks
it&#39;s going to.

00:35:57.770 --> 00:36:02.090
The other piece, besides
focus for

00:36:02.090 --> 00:36:04.050
execution is intensity.

00:36:04.050 --> 00:36:08.660
Um, startups only work at a
fairly intense level.

00:36:08.660 --> 00:36:12.170
Um, a friend of mine says
that the secret to startups

00:36:12.170 --> 00:36:14.890
is extreme focus and extreme
dedication.

00:36:14.890 --> 00:36:16.300
You know you can like a have
a startup in one

00:36:16.300 --> 00:36:18.320
other thing, you can have a
startup in a family but

00:36:18.320 --> 00:36:21.380
you probably can&#39;t have many
other hobbies.

00:36:21.380 --> 00:36:23.980
Startups are not the best
choice for

00:36:23.980 --> 00:36:25.400
work life balance.

00:36:25.400 --> 00:36:27.160
And that&#39;s sort of just, the
sad reality.

00:36:27.160 --> 00:36:29.760
Um, there&#39;s a lot of great
things about a startup, but

00:36:29.760 --> 00:36:31.020
this is not one of them.

00:36:31.020 --> 00:36:32.100
Um, they are all consuming
in

00:36:32.100 --> 00:36:34.330
a way that is difficult to
explain.

00:36:34.330 --> 00:36:35.250
You, you generally need to

00:36:35.250 --> 00:36:36.770
be willing to outwork your
competitors.

00:36:38.270 --> 00:36:41.580
The good news here, uh, why
that&#39;s hard to see um, is

00:36:41.580 --> 00:36:45.530
that a small amount of extra
work on the right thing.

00:36:45.530 --> 00:36:47.220
Makes a huge difference.

00:36:47.220 --> 00:36:49.540
One example that I like to
give is thinking about

00:36:49.540 --> 00:36:52.700
the viral coefficient for a
consumer web product.

00:36:52.700 --> 00:36:56.110
Um, how many users how many
new users each

00:36:56.110 --> 00:36:57.098
existing user brings in.

00:36:57.098 --> 00:36:59.550
If it&#39;s .99 the company will

00:36:59.550 --> 00:37:01.600
eventually flatline and then
die.

00:37:01.600 --> 00:37:04.590
Uh, and if it&#39;s 1.01 you&#39;ll
be in this happy place of

00:37:04.590 --> 00:37:06.390
exponential growth forever.

00:37:06.390 --> 00:37:09.230
Um, so this is just one
concrete example of where

00:37:09.230 --> 00:37:12.150
a tiny bit of extra work is
the difference between

00:37:12.150 --> 00:37:13.470
success and failure.

00:37:13.470 --> 00:37:15.760
And, when we talk to
successful founders they

00:37:15.760 --> 00:37:18.110
tell stories like this all
the time.

00:37:18.110 --> 00:37:20.150
You know, just outworking
their competitors by

00:37:20.150 --> 00:37:22.770
a little bit, was what made
them successful.

00:37:24.600 --> 00:37:27.530
Um, so you have to be really
intense, you know,

00:37:27.530 --> 00:37:29.000
this only comes from the
CEO,

00:37:29.000 --> 00:37:30.750
this only comes from the
founders.

00:37:30.750 --> 00:37:33.090
Uh, one of the biggest
advantages that

00:37:33.090 --> 00:37:35.450
startups have is execution
speed and

00:37:35.450 --> 00:37:38.240
you have to have this
relentless operating rhythm.

00:37:38.240 --> 00:37:42.590
Um, Facebook has this famous
that says, move fast and

00:37:42.590 --> 00:37:43.250
break things.

00:37:44.280 --> 00:37:46.300
Um, but at the same time,

00:37:46.300 --> 00:37:47.630
they manage to be obsessed
with quality.

00:37:47.630 --> 00:37:49.100
And this is why it&#39;s hard.

00:37:49.100 --> 00:37:52.280
It&#39;s easy to move fast or be
obsessed with quality.

00:37:52.280 --> 00:37:53.160
Um, the trick is

00:37:53.160 --> 00:37:55.570
that you have to do both at
a start up.

00:37:55.570 --> 00:37:57.280
Um, you need to have a
culture where

00:37:57.280 --> 00:37:59.520
people have very high
quality standards for

00:37:59.520 --> 00:38:02.870
everything the company does
but still move quickly.

00:38:02.870 --> 00:38:03.800
Ah, Apple Facebook and

00:38:03.800 --> 00:38:05.300
Google have all done this
extremely well.

00:38:06.790 --> 00:38:08.810
It&#39;s not just about the
product um,

00:38:08.810 --> 00:38:10.200
it&#39;s about everything they
do.

00:38:10.200 --> 00:38:11.780
They move fast and they
break things and

00:38:11.780 --> 00:38:13.520
they&#39;re frugal in the right
places.

00:38:13.520 --> 00:38:15.390
But they care about quality
everywhere.

00:38:15.390 --> 00:38:17.430
Um, you know you don&#39;t buy
people shitty computers if

00:38:17.430 --> 00:38:19.110
you don&#39;t want them to write
shitty code.

00:38:19.110 --> 00:38:20.170
You really have to you do
have to

00:38:20.170 --> 00:38:22.640
set a quality bar that runs
through the entire company.

00:38:25.280 --> 00:38:27.880
Related to this is that you
have to be decisive.

00:38:27.880 --> 00:38:30.550
Um, indecisiveness is a
start up killer.

00:38:30.550 --> 00:38:32.570
Mediocre founders spend a
lot of time talking about

00:38:32.570 --> 00:38:35.930
grand plans but they never
quite make this decision.

00:38:35.930 --> 00:38:37.320
You know, they&#39;re, they&#39;re
talking about well I

00:38:37.320 --> 00:38:38.580
could do this thing that
sounds great or

00:38:38.580 --> 00:38:39.440
I could do this other thing.

00:38:39.440 --> 00:38:42.150
And they keep going back and
forth and they don&#39;t act.

00:38:42.150 --> 00:38:44.870
Now what you actually need
is this bias towards action.

00:38:44.870 --> 00:38:48.420
Um, the best founders work
on things that seem small,

00:38:48.420 --> 00:38:50.530
but they move really
quickly, uh,

00:38:50.530 --> 00:38:52.270
they get things done really
quickly.

00:38:52.270 --> 00:38:55.560
Every time you talk to the
best founders, they,

00:38:55.560 --> 00:38:56.980
they&#39;ve got new things done.

00:38:56.980 --> 00:39:00.280
In fact, this is the one
thing that we learned

00:39:00.280 --> 00:39:03.120
best predicts success of
founders in YC.

00:39:04.200 --> 00:39:06.370
If every time we talk to a
team they&#39;ve gotten new

00:39:06.370 --> 00:39:09.470
things done that&#39;s the best
predictor we have of

00:39:09.470 --> 00:39:11.180
the company will go on to be
successful.

