Part of this is that you can
do huge things by,

00:39:16.910 --> 00:39:18.490
in incremental pieces.

00:39:18.490 --> 00:39:19.620
If you just keep knocking
down

00:39:19.620 --> 00:39:21.320
small chunks one at a time.

00:39:21.320 --> 00:39:22.610
In an year you look back
you&#39;ve done

00:39:22.610 --> 00:39:24.300
this amazing thing.

00:39:24.300 --> 00:39:25.740
On the other hand if you
disappear for an year.

00:39:25.740 --> 00:39:28.030
And you expect to come back
with something amazing all

00:39:28.030 --> 00:39:30.930
at once it usually never
happens.

00:39:30.930 --> 00:39:32.920
You have to pick these right
sized projects.

00:39:32.920 --> 00:39:33.880
You know even if you&#39;re
building this

00:39:33.880 --> 00:39:35.910
crazy synthetic biology
company.

00:39:35.910 --> 00:39:37.640
Um, most people would say
well I have to go away for

00:39:37.640 --> 00:39:38.970
an year, I can&#39;t do this
incrementally.

00:39:39.970 --> 00:39:41.378
There is almost always a way
to break it down,

00:39:41.378 --> 00:39:45.030
into smaller projects.

00:39:45.030 --> 00:39:48.190
Um, so speed is this huge
premium, right?

00:39:48.190 --> 00:39:50.200
The, the best founders
usually respond to email,

00:39:50.200 --> 00:39:51.340
the most quickly.

00:39:51.340 --> 00:39:52.630
Um, they make decisions the
most quickly.

00:39:52.630 --> 00:39:55.450
They&#39;re generally quick in
all these different ways.

00:39:55.450 --> 00:39:57.020
Um, and they just have this
do

00:39:57.020 --> 00:39:58.110
whatever it takes attitude.

00:39:59.770 --> 00:40:01.060
They also show up a lot.

00:40:01.060 --> 00:40:03.960
Um, they come to you know,
they come to

00:40:03.960 --> 00:40:06.490
meetings they come in they
meet us in person.

00:40:06.490 --> 00:40:09.980
Um, one piece of advice uh,
that I have.

00:40:09.980 --> 00:40:12.160
It&#39;s always worked for me is
that they get on planes in

00:40:12.160 --> 00:40:13.680
marginal situations.

00:40:13.680 --> 00:40:15.780
Um, how we doing on time?

00:40:15.780 --> 00:40:17.130
I&#39;ll tell a quick story
here.

00:40:17.130 --> 00:40:20.330
Uh, when I was running my
own company um,

00:40:20.330 --> 00:40:21.830
we found out that we were
about to lose a deal.

00:40:21.830 --> 00:40:24.580
And it was sort of this,
this critical deal from

00:40:24.580 --> 00:40:26.650
the first big customer in
the space.

00:40:26.650 --> 00:40:29.030
Uh, and it was gonna go to
this company that had

00:40:29.030 --> 00:40:31.050
been around for years before
we were.

00:40:31.050 --> 00:40:32.480
Um, and they had us, like,
all locked up.

00:40:33.610 --> 00:40:34.220
So we called.
We said,

00:40:34.220 --> 00:40:35.070
hey we have this better
product.

00:40:35.070 --> 00:40:35.820
You gotta meet with us.

00:40:35.820 --> 00:40:36.520
They said, you know what.

00:40:36.520 --> 00:40:37.780
We&#39;re signing this deal
tomorrow.

00:40:37.780 --> 00:40:38.590
Sorry.

00:40:38.590 --> 00:40:40.220
Um, we drove to the airport.

00:40:40.220 --> 00:40:41.140
We got on a plane.

00:40:41.140 --> 00:40:44.050
Um, we were at their office
at 6AM the next morning.

00:40:44.050 --> 00:40:45.010
We just sat there.

00:40:45.010 --> 00:40:45.980
They told us to go away.

00:40:45.980 --> 00:40:47.400
We just kept sitting there.

00:40:47.400 --> 00:40:49.110
Um, finally one of the
junior guys decided to

00:40:49.110 --> 00:40:50.110
meet with us.

00:40:50.110 --> 00:40:51.530
Um, finally after that,

00:40:51.530 --> 00:40:53.590
one of the senior guys
decided to meet with us.

00:40:53.590 --> 00:40:54.680
They ended up ripping up the
contract and

00:40:54.680 --> 00:40:55.560
sell their company.

00:40:55.560 --> 00:40:56.790
Um, and we closed the deal

00:40:56.790 --> 00:40:58.390
with them about a week
later.

00:40:58.390 --> 00:41:01.290
Uh, and I&#39;m sure that had we
not gotten on a plane,

00:41:01.290 --> 00:41:03.020
had we not shown up in
person,

00:41:03.020 --> 00:41:04.710
that would not have worked
out.

00:41:04.710 --> 00:41:07.740
Um, and so you just sort of
like, you show up,

00:41:07.740 --> 00:41:09.380
you do these things, you
know.

00:41:09.380 --> 00:41:12.420
Uh, it&#39;s, when people say
get on planes in marginal

00:41:12.420 --> 00:41:14.400
situations they usually mean
it.

00:41:14.400 --> 00:41:17.130
Uh, well they don&#39;t usually
mean it literally but

00:41:17.130 --> 00:41:18.700
I think it&#39;s actually good
literal advice.

00:41:20.210 --> 00:41:22.040
Um, all right.

00:41:22.040 --> 00:41:23.570
&gt;&gt; Six minutes, so.

00:41:23.570 --> 00:41:24.830
&gt;&gt; I&#39;ll skip that part then.

00:41:27.740 --> 00:41:30.840
So, I mentioned this
momentum and growth earlier.

00:41:30.840 --> 00:41:33.390
Uh, once more, that momentum
and

00:41:33.390 --> 00:41:36.670
growth are the lifeblood of
startups.

00:41:36.670 --> 00:41:38.520
Um, this is the,

00:41:38.520 --> 00:41:42.300
probably in the top three
secrets to executing well.

00:41:42.300 --> 00:41:45.390
You want a company to be
winning all the time.

00:41:45.390 --> 00:41:47.440
If you ever take your foot
off the gas pedal,

00:41:47.440 --> 00:41:50.170
things will spiral out of
control, snowball downwards.

00:41:50.170 --> 00:41:52.930
Um, a winning team feels
good and keeps winning.

00:41:52.930 --> 00:41:55.190
A team that hasn&#39;t won in a
while gets demotivated and

00:41:55.190 --> 00:41:55.720
keeps losing.

00:41:56.810 --> 00:41:59.530
So always keep momentum is
this prime directive for

00:41:59.530 --> 00:42:00.770
managing a start up.

00:42:00.770 --> 00:42:03.950
Um, if I can only tell
founders one thing

00:42:03.950 --> 00:42:06.990
about how to, how to run a
company, it would be this.

00:42:06.990 --> 00:42:07.770
For most start,

00:42:07.770 --> 00:42:11.160
software startups, this
translates to keep growing.

00:42:11.160 --> 00:42:13.620
For hardware startups it
translates to don&#39;t let

00:42:13.620 --> 00:42:15.190
your ship date slip.

00:42:15.190 --> 00:42:17.280
Um, this is what we tell
people during YC,

00:42:17.280 --> 00:42:20.260
and they usually listen,
everything is good.

00:42:20.260 --> 00:42:22.780
Um, what happens after the
end of YC is

00:42:22.780 --> 00:42:25.160
that they get distracted on
other things.

00:42:25.160 --> 00:42:26.090
And then growth slows down.

00:42:27.260 --> 00:42:30.760
And somehow after that
happens,

00:42:30.760 --> 00:42:32.950
people start getting unhappy
and quitting and

00:42:32.950 --> 00:42:34.330
then everything falls apart.

00:42:36.020 --> 00:42:36.780
It&#39;s hard to figure out

00:42:36.780 --> 00:42:39.640
a growth engine because most
companies grow in new ways.

00:42:39.640 --> 00:42:41.550
Um, but there is this thing
about if you

00:42:41.550 --> 00:42:43.260
built a good product, it
will grow.

00:42:43.260 --> 00:42:45.210
And so getting this good,
this product right at the

00:42:45.210 --> 00:42:47.580
beginning is the best way to
not lose momentum later.

00:42:49.240 --> 00:42:50.640
If you do lose momentum,

00:42:50.640 --> 00:42:52.400
most founders try to get it
back in the wrong way.

00:42:54.810 --> 00:42:57.300
They give these long
speeches about vision for

00:42:57.300 --> 00:42:57.840
the company and

00:42:57.840 --> 00:43:00.450
they try to rally the troops
with, with speeches.

00:43:00.450 --> 00:43:03.120
Um, but employees in a
company where momentum has

00:43:03.120 --> 00:43:04.750
sagged don&#39;t wanna hear
that.

00:43:04.750 --> 00:43:07.180
Um, you have to save the
vision speeches for

00:43:07.180 --> 00:43:08.010
when the company&#39;s winning.

00:43:09.030 --> 00:43:10.060
When you&#39;re not winning,

00:43:10.060 --> 00:43:12.820
you just have to get
momentum back in small wins.

00:43:12.820 --> 00:43:15.160
Um, a board member of mine
used to say that sales fix

00:43:15.160 --> 00:43:18.170
everything in a startup, and
that is really true.

00:43:18.170 --> 00:43:19.790
So you figure out where you
can get these small wins,

00:43:19.790 --> 00:43:21.310
and you get that done.

00:43:21.310 --> 00:43:22.330
And then you&#39;ll be amazed
how

00:43:22.330 --> 00:43:23.950
all the other problems in a
startup disappear.

00:43:25.340 --> 00:43:27.170
Uh, another thing that
you&#39;ll notice if you

00:43:27.170 --> 00:43:28.760
have momentum sag is that

00:43:28.760 --> 00:43:30.670
everyone starts disagreeing
about what to do.

00:43:30.670 --> 00:43:33.300
Fights come out when a
company loses momentum.

00:43:33.300 --> 00:43:37.810
Uh, and so a framework for
that that I think works is.

00:43:37.810 --> 00:43:39.470
That when there&#39;s
disagreement among the team

00:43:39.470 --> 00:43:42.830
about what to do, then you
ask your users and

00:43:42.830 --> 00:43:43.960
you do whatever your users
tell you.

00:43:43.960 --> 00:43:46.590
And you have to remind
people like, hey, stuffs not

00:43:46.590 --> 00:43:48.620
working right now we don&#39;t
actually hate each other.

00:43:48.620 --> 00:43:50.650
Um, we just need to get back
on track and

00:43:50.650 --> 00:43:51.300
everything will work.

00:43:51.300 --> 00:43:53.910
And if you just call it out,
if you just acknowledge that

00:43:53.910 --> 00:43:57.270
um, you&#39;ll find that things
will get way better.

00:43:57.270 --> 00:43:59.470
To use a Facebook example
again,

00:43:59.470 --> 00:44:02.120
when Facebook&#39;s growth
slowed in 2008

00:44:02.120 --> 00:44:04.090
Mark instituted a growth
group.

00:44:04.090 --> 00:44:05.610
They worked on very small
things to

00:44:05.610 --> 00:44:07.600
make Facebook real faster.

00:44:07.600 --> 00:44:09.330
Uh, all of these things by
themselves seemed really

00:44:09.330 --> 00:44:12.130
small, but they got the, the
curve of Facebook back up.

00:44:13.150 --> 00:44:14.400
Um, it quickly became the
most

00:44:14.400 --> 00:44:15.690
prestigious group there.

00:44:15.690 --> 00:44:17.280
Um, Marcus said that it&#39;s
been one of

00:44:17.280 --> 00:44:19.900
Facebook&#39;s best innovations.

00:44:19.900 --> 00:44:21.840
Um, according to friends of
mine that worked at

00:44:21.840 --> 00:44:22.990
Facebook at the time.

00:44:22.990 --> 00:44:25.010
It really turned around the
dynamic of the company.

00:44:25.010 --> 00:44:26.370
And went from this thing
where everyone was

00:44:26.370 --> 00:44:27.510
feeling bad and

00:44:27.510 --> 00:44:29.790
the momentum was gone, back
to a place that was winning.

00:44:31.980 --> 00:44:36.270
So a good way to to keep
momentum is to

00:44:36.270 --> 00:44:38.730
establish an operating
rhythm in the company early.

00:44:38.730 --> 00:44:40.020
Where you ship product and

00:44:40.020 --> 00:44:42.220
lauch new features on this
regular basis.

00:44:42.220 --> 00:44:43.990
Uh, where you&#39;re reviewing
metrics you know,

00:44:43.990 --> 00:44:45.790
every week with the entire
company.

00:44:45.790 --> 00:44:46.800
Uh, this is actually one of

00:44:46.800 --> 00:44:48.068
the best things your board
can do for you.

00:44:48.068 --> 00:44:51.740
Um, boards add value to

00:44:51.740 --> 00:44:53.810
business strategy only
rarely.

00:44:53.810 --> 00:44:54.540
Um, but

00:44:54.540 --> 00:44:57.390
very frequently, you can use
them as a forcing function,

00:44:57.390 --> 00:44:59.171
to get the company to care
about metrics,

00:44:59.171 --> 00:45:03.454
and milestones.

00:45:03.454 --> 00:45:05.750
Um, one thing that often
disrupts momentum and

00:45:05.750 --> 00:45:08.920
really shouldn&#39;t is
competitors.

00:45:08.920 --> 00:45:11.130
Competitors making noise in
the press, I think,

00:45:11.130 --> 00:45:14.070
probably crushes a company&#39;s
momentum more often than

00:45:14.070 --> 00:45:15.910
any other external factor.

00:45:15.910 --> 00:45:17.720
Um, so here&#39;s a good rule of
thumb.

00:45:17.720 --> 00:45:20.040
Don&#39;t worry about a
competitor at all.

00:45:20.040 --> 00:45:22.700
Um, until they&#39;re actually
leaving you with a real,

00:45:22.700 --> 00:45:24.180
shipped product.

00:45:24.180 --> 00:45:26.080
Uh, press releases are
easier to write than code,

00:45:27.140 --> 00:45:29.730
um, and that is still easier
than making a great product.

00:45:29.730 --> 00:45:31.800
So remind your company of
this, and don&#39;t, this is

00:45:31.800 --> 00:45:34.480
sort of a founders rule, is
not to let the company get

00:45:34.480 --> 00:45:37.340
down because of the
competitors and the press.

00:45:37.340 --> 00:45:41.130
Um, this great quote from
Henry Ford that I love.

00:45:41.130 --> 00:45:42.811
The competitor to be feared
is

00:45:42.811 --> 00:45:45.038
one who never bothers about
you at all.

00:45:45.038 --> 00:45:46.019
But goes on making his own

00:45:46.019 --> 00:45:47.900
business better all the
time.

00:45:47.900 --> 00:45:49.910
These are almost never the
companies that put out

00:45:49.910 --> 00:45:53.660
a lot of press releases, and
they bum people out.

